metadata.name: Siesta #81
metadata.description:
Siesta is a mesmerizing loop creating an organic shape.  The radius, frequency and amplitude of each lines are generated for each token, along with the color theme. Some rare items are available.
 Each shape is randomly filled.

 Created by Quentin Hocdé, in Napoli (Italia).

metadata.name: n Forms #221
metadata.description:
Hand-scrawled documentation of abstract structures. A journal from another realm.

Press 's' to save an image while in full-screen mode.

If you want to increase the resolution of the saved image, add e.g. &size=2000 after the live/fullscreen view URL to render the canvas at that specific pixel width (default = browser sized). This will be dependent on your system specifications, but outputs of up to 8000px wide, or above, should be possible.

Usually loads best in Chrome

metadata.name: Klyft #864
metadata.description:
“Klyft” is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel.

Klyft is a juxtaposition of two different projections for the future. One, made by the World Economic Forum, suggests that the global gender gap will have closed by the year 2154. The other, by the UN IPCC, estimates that global warming will reach 3.2 degrees celcius by the year 2100.

Klyft makes use of the unique temporal aspect of computational art by developing its expression gradually over the next 132 years. As we come closer to 2154, the space between the two shapes in Klyft will grow smaller to symbolize the closing of the gender gap. As time goes on, however, Klyft also becomes more and more glitched out to represent the projected increases in greenhouse gases and climate catastrophes.

In the end, Klyft’s expression will be heavily corrupted, and the two shapes will have reached each other.

· URL parameters ·

You can add the following parameters to the URL to change the behavior of the piece.

date=<YYYY-MM-DD> — See how Klyft looks on another day. Use the format YYYY-MM-DD. 

color=<number> — See the piece in another color scheme. The numbers loop around, so 17 equals 0, 18 equals 1, etc. 

resolution=<number> — View the piece in a higher resolution. 1 is normal resolution, 2 is double, etc. No decimals allowed.

image=true — Save the piece as an image. 

record=true — Save the piece as a video in WEBM format.

Adding the following URL parameters will show Klyft in double resolution on the day gender equality is achieved according to the WEF:

date=2154-01-01&resolution=2

Adding the following URL parameters will save a video of Klyft in the ‘Stokkendahl Dalgas’ color scheme:

color=14&record=true

· Interactions ·

Pressing the following keys will trigger functionality as well as add related URL parameters automatically. 

Pressing D will increment the date by 1 year.

Pressing C will increment the color index by 1.

Pressing R will toggle between normal and double resolution.

Pressing I will toggle the image URL parameter, which saves the piece as an image. Only works outside of iframe.

Pressing V will toggle the video URL parameter, which saves the piece as a video. Only works outside of iframe.

There are secret key presses as well. Some of them only work outside of iframe. 

· Accessibility ·

Klyft is built to support screen readers. It has been tested using MacOS’ VoiceOver, and uses p5.js’ describeElement() to provide screen reader functionality.

If you have any comments (good or bad) on the screen reader integration, don’t hesitate to reach out on my Twitter: @ada_ada_ada_art. 

· Credits and license ·

Klyft is made with p5.js.

Klyft is licensed under a modified version of the Climate Strike License (CSL).

metadata.name: 7VV1N5 #81
metadata.description:
GO BIG OR GO HOME.

After a week of minimalism code, our hero, the handsome artist Daniel, decided he needed something involving maximalism to reset the balance. Finding pairs to put together is satisfying.

Images will take 6-9 seconds to display and refresh between window resizing.

Use the z key or single click/tap to switch to "zoom" mode, which zooms in and fills the viewport; use z & tap/click to cycle through views. Use x and double-click/tap to go back to square mode.

Note: It doesn't work on Internet Explorer, because Microsoft. iOS is faster than Android.

-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

z, click, tap - Switch to & cycle "zoom" mode
x, double-click, double-tap - Switch back out of "zoom" mode.
h - Toggle high-res (slow)
s - Download and save image (takes a few seconds, longer for high-res)

metadata.name: MindFlow #145
metadata.description:
Consciousness flows over our mind, just like Karma goes through our body, which creates our life.

--------------------

This is an abstract generation made by pure code.

--------------------

In live mode, press 's' or 'S' to save a high resolution png (3000*4500).

Please be patient with drawing process and have fun with its tiny logo animation.
I hope you like this work and enjoy exploring your own mindflow.

Endlessworld 2022

metadata.name: MetaMountains #57
metadata.description:
Beautiful MetaMountains to stare and escape from reality, sometimes they will look like any other mountain, and Sometimes while you look at them you will have the feeling of seeing the terrain of a planet in a distant galaxy.

Is that a regular mountain? No! It's a MetaMountain! You may even witness the rise of two suns or two moons.

No fancy features, just waves, and shapes with 8 hand-picked color schemes. Sit back and enjoy.

----

Color schemes:

[] Japan Mountains
[] Farm Mountains
[] Summer Mountains
[] Carbon Mountains
[] Arizona Mountains
[] Nordic Mountains
[] MonoDay Mountains
[] MonoNight Mountains

metadata.name: The Artifact #413
metadata.description:
An archaeological artifact from the future, when many everyday objects are produced by generative algorithms. Some artifacts are in one piece, and others are fragmented. The color palettes are named after the rivers where artifacts in this design have first been discovered.

URL and interactive features:

- Append &r=<number> to the URL to change the image resolution. For example, &r=0.5 will halve the pixel count along both width and height, and &r=2 will double it.

- Append &d=<number> to the URL to change the pixel density. For example, &d=0.3 will generate a very quick, coarse render, and &d=2 will generate very fine stippling.

- Append &p to the URL to reveal detailed parameter settings used for the artwork.

- Append &h to the URL to suppress the notification that rendering is in progress.

- Press 's' in the live view to save the rendered image as a png.

The generative code is written in plain JavaScript. Polygon boundaries are determined via t-SNE, which is implemented in AssemblyScript and compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) for maximum performance. No external libraries have been used. Licensed CC0.

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

metadata.name: Penumbra #79
metadata.description:
Penumbra is a geometric exploration of the possible outcomes from 3 basic rules:

1) Place some walls
2) Place some light sources
3) Draw the resulting shadows

This series is a small thank you to the collectors of Umbra :)

metadata.name: Here When You Need Me #213
metadata.description:
'Here When You Need Me' is a generative system that creates...

Good question, and I think the answer is up to you. Jewels? Reflections? The Sand in a Life's Hourglass?

Who knows. The truth is that I didn't have anything in mind for the project, and where it has ended up was purely through exploration, and a refinement of simple methods.

By the end, it has become exactly what I needed it to be, and the results of this project give me an encouragement that is difficult to explain.

Now, one of the primary features of the project is your ability to make it what you need. Several URL arguments are explained below that will allow you to tweak your edition's distortion and resolution.

15% of primary sales will be donated to 'Girls Who Code'
15% of primary sales will be donated to 'Cure Parkinson's'

10% of royalties will go to 'Girls Who Code'
10% of royalties will go to 'Cure Parkinson's'
10% of royalties will go to the original minter

Thank you everyone.


Options
-------
Parameters can be appended to the live URL to adjust the output's distortion, resolution, border size, and border color. These are all fun to play with, and can be used in combination to showcase the variability and potential of each piece.

'&distortion=#': Adjust distortion, any value from 0.0 to 3.0 (Use 0 to see a 'flat' version of the image)
'&resolution=#': Multiplier for width/height, any value from 0.1 to 6.0 (Soft max of 3.9)
'&borderSize=#': Multiplier for border size, any value from 0.0 to 3.0 (Use 0 for no border)
'&borderColor=ffffff': Custom border color, any 6 character hex code (Do not include '#')

An example of using multiple options would be '&resolution=2&distortion=.5'

Please check the linked fx(text) article for detailed examples on using these options.


Distortion
----------
I wanted to provide some amount of control to take advantage of the possibilities of generative art. 'Here When You Need Me' starts off at a certain point, but allows you to adjust the distortion to your favorite level.

Using '&distortion=0' will show the underlying shapes.


Resolution / Printing
---------------------
'Here When You Need Me' looks best with at least '&resolution=2' and is designed to support printing. Remember that parameters can be provided to adjust the border attributes as well.

Ideally, you should aim for 300 'pixels per inch' for a decent quality print. Default resolution is 1800x2400.

'&resolution=1' -> 6"x8"
'&resolution=2' -> 12"x16"

Some quick math will give you the correct modifier if you start with the width in inches of your desired print. 

(inches) * (ppi) / (default width)

An important note, the maximum resolution modifier I've had success with is 3.9 because of the browser's image size limitations, but the capability is still in the code to go higher in case it is helpful to someone.

If you have your edition printed, please share with me because it would make me incredibly happy to see it!


---------
Thank you to everyone for your support and contributions. 

I put way more detail in this description than I intended, but if you want even more, you can read about the development and potential of this project in the accompanying fx(text) article, once it is written.

Created by Walter Anderson (@noxiarb)

metadata.name: Sketch Book #59
metadata.description:
Sketch Book is a generative collection that imagines an abstract sketch built with lines and shapes in harmony with each other.

It’s called Sketch Book as it started with me sketching a bunch of lines in p5.js and then warping them to give them a natural waviness. The artwork combines subdivision and domain warping techniques before drawing the final lines and shapes on the canvas. 

Sketch Book renders as a fixed resolution output (1000x1200px). Controls (in live view): 

Press [2] to render at 2000x2400px
Press [4] to render at 4000x4800px
Press [8] to render at 8000x9600px
Press [s] to save the current view (default or higher resolution image)

metadata.name: Richter #107
metadata.description:
Richter is the second collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog, following their first project called Gerhard. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time.
 
Richter works with data from 4 of 24 highres images, 30mb in total. This is the maximum size fxhash allows for a project and three times more than Gerhard. Richard Nadler created stunning new textures, enabling more variation in composition and detail to emerge at much higher resolution. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Richter elevates the approach from Gerhard with new methods for the realtime rendering process and new features like offline-first caching. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels as data.
 
Richter is featured in the exhibition "Generative Abstraction" at Expanded.art in Berlin.
 
- Click to start a new layer of motion and color.
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen.
- Press “s” to save the canvas.
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

leanderherzog.ch/2023/richter/
leanderherzog.ch/2022/gerhard/
fxhash.xyz/generative/17030/

metadata.name: The Oneiroi #100
metadata.description:
The Oneiroi(Gods of Dreams), by NJT

The Oneiroi is inspired by Roman ancient Gods which ia a unique digital-hand-drawing that can Randomly Generate.

The Oneiroi collection contains Traits 26 (141 layers), and it can make your own unique NFT.

These NFTs are randomly minted, which is a chance for everyone to get a rare version.


Don't hesitate to send me DM on twitter for more info : @mahdi_njt
